source_description_synonym: R PHS IP CARDIAC INTERVAL PR
reviewer_comment: "PR interval feature" suggests the morphology, shape or the PR interval segment, where as "PR interval" may encompass the meaning of the duration of th PR segment in time
author_comment: The target concept was chosen because of its associated synonyms, notably "PR interval", which specifically does not include the word "feature." Furthermore, this concept falls under the broader category of "ECG waveform" SNOMED CT term (https://athena.ohdsi.org/search-terms/terms/4064624), which also encompasses descendants like "interval duration," indicating that the features of ECG waveforms extend beyond their morphology.

source_description_synonym: R PHS IP CARDIAC INTERVAL QRS
reviewer_comment: The two concepts are identical in wording and represents likely the QRS time interval

source_description_synonym: R PHS IP CARDIAC INTERVAL QT
R PHS IP CARDIAC INTERVAL QTC
reviewer_comment: potential typo (QTS vs. QTC) in the source data. Regardless of the potential typo, QT interval is not the same as QT interval corrected, because corrected means corrected for heart rate and the two parameters will always be numerically different
author_comment: While the source description is formulated as "CARDIAC | INTERVAL | QTS Interval", in the subject_synonym_source field, we can observe a variation of this source: "R PHS IP CARDIAC INTERVAL QTC," where "QTC" refers to the "Q-T corrected interval". This representation is accurately reflected in the mapping.

source_description: CARDIAC | Pulse contour analysis | Cardiac OUTPUT (CO)
source_description_synonym: R CARDIAC OUTPUT/ R PHS IP PULSE CONTOUT ANALYSIS CO
target_concept_name: Monitoring of cardiac output using pulse contour analysis
reviewer_comment: I think the two terms imply the same concept; although the presence of the " | " between the words Pulse Contour Analysis and Cardiac Output make the concept a bit unclear as to what exactly it implies- the science of pulse contour analysis (which is done to calcular cardiac output) or cardiac output, the numerical value itself?
author_comment: Based on the source description, we can infer that cardiac output was measured, with pulse contour analysis being employed as the measurement method. This detail becomes significant when we aim to compare cardiac output values obtained through various modalities (e.g. pulse contour analysis vs. echocardiography), that can be relevant when evaluating the effectiveness of treatments, the measurement precision, assessing the hemodynamic stability of the patient, and predicting patient ouctomes.

reviewer_comment: The word "feature" in target concept implies the different components, morphologies, wave appearnce. "Cardiac rhythm" in source code is fairly clear, meaning what is the rhythm- sinus, bradycardia, atrial fibrillation, etc
author_comment: The term "Feature of Heart Rhythm" was selected due to the absence of detailed attributes of heart rhythm measurement in the source description. Such attributes could detail the rhythm's origin (e.g., sinus, atrial, junctional, ventricular), its regularity pattern (either regular or irregular), and its quantitative rate (categorized as normal, bradycardia, or tachycardia).

reviewer_comment: While cardiac sound is a rarely used term, the two concepts can be interchangeable semantically
